</lyxtabular>

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

This brane configuration is lifted in M-theory to M5-branes, wrapped on
 a cylinder with 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 punctures created by intersecting M5-branes.
 Therefore, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=2$
\end_inset

 linear quiver theory is obtained by compactification of the 6d 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=\left(2,0\right)$
\end_inset

 theory of type 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{N-1}$
\end_inset

 on a cylinder with 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 punctures, or a sphere with 
\begin_inset Formula $m+2$
\end_inset

 punctures.
 We distinguish the two punctures coming from the ends of the cylinder from
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 punctures in between.
 They are referred to as maximal and minimal punctures, respectively.
 In the class-
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

 language, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=2$
\end_inset

 linear quiver theory is a theory associated to a sphere with 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 maximal and 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 minimal punctures, see figure.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
R-symmetry of the theory is 
\begin_inset Formula $SU(2)_{I}\times U(1)_{r}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $SU(2)_{I}$
\end_inset

 represents the rotation symmetry of the 789-space, and 
\begin_inset Formula $U(1)_{r}$
\end_inset

 the rotation symmetry of the 45-plane.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $SU(N)$
\end_inset

 flavor node from each end of the quiver is associated to the maximal puncture
 on the corresponding side of the sphere.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th gauge node is associated to the tube between the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th and 
\begin_inset Formula $(i+1)$
\end_inset

th minimal punctures.
 To the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th minimal puncture is associated a flavor symmetry 
\begin_inset Formula $U(1)_{i}$
\end_inset

 which acts on the hypermultiplet charged under the 
\begin_inset Formula $(i-1)$
\end_inset

th and 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th gauge nodes.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Following the philosophy of class-
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

 theories, we decompose this theory into basic building blocks by decoupling
 gauge fields.
 Roughly, the gauge coupling of the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th gauge node is inversely proportional to the length between the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th and 
\begin_inset Formula $(i+1)$
\end_inset

th minimal punctures.
 To make the gauge couplings small, we take the minimal punctures far apart
 from one another.
 Then the surface looks like a string of 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 spheres, each containing a single minimal puncture, connected by long tubes.
 The smaller the gauge couplings get, the longer the tubes become, and eventuall
y these spheres split up as the couplings go to zero.
 Each of the spheres represents a bifundamental hypermultiplet, which is
 a linear quiver with 
\begin_inset Formula $m=1$
\end_inset

, so it has one minimal and two maximal punctures.
 The quiver thus breaks into a collection of three-punctured spheres, or
 trinions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Conversely, a sphere with two maximal and 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 minimal punctures is obtained by gluing 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 trinions together, namely by replacing pairs of maximal punctures with
 tubes.
 In general, we can connect two Riemann surfaces with a tube at maximal
 punctures.
 From the point of view of gauge theory, gluing corresponds to gauging the
 diagonal combination of the SU(N) flavor symmetries associated to the maximal
 punctures involved.
 Using trinions with one minimal and two maximal punctures, we can obtain
 any linear quiver in this way, and for that manner also a circular quiver
 by further gluing the two ends of a linear quiver together.
 In this sense, these trinions are building blocks for linear and circular
 quivers.
 As these two kinds of quivers can be treated essentially in the same manner,
 we will focus on linear quivers in the followings.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To make contact with brane tilings, what we need to do is to find the counterpar
t of trinion, building block of quiver gauge theories, in brane tiling systems.
 To do this, we describe the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=2$
\end_inset

 linear quiver theory as an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=1$
\end_inset

 quiver gauge theory.
 In terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=1$
\end_inset

 supermultiplets, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=2$
\end_inset

 vector multiplet for the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th gauge node decomposes into a vector multiplet and a chiral multiplet
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{i}$
\end_inset

 in the adjoint representation with 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(r,I_{3}\right)=\left(-1,0\right)$
\end_inset

, while the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th hypermultiplet consists of two bifundamental chiral multiplets 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{i},\,\tilde{Q}_{i}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(r,I_{3}\right)=\left(0,1/2\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Here 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{3}$
\end_inset

 is a Cartan generator of 
\begin_inset Formula $SU(2)_{I}$
\end_inset

.
 The pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(Q_{i},\tilde{Q}_{i}^{\dagger})$
\end_inset

 transforms in the doublet of 
\begin_inset Formula $SU(2)_{I}$
\end_inset

 and have 
\begin_inset Formula $U(1)_{i}$
\end_inset

 charge 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{i}=-1$
\end_inset

.
 From the point of view of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=1$
\end_inset

 supersymmetry, the U(1) symmetry generated by the combination 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{F}=r+I_{3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

is a flavor symmetry.
 We denote the fugacity for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 For the standard definition of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=2$
\end_inset

 index, 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 enter the trace through the combination 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(pq\right)^{-r}t^{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

.
 THen, the fugacities of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{i},\,\tilde{Q}_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{i}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{t}/\alpha_{i}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{t}\alpha_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $pq/t$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is helpful for us to prepare two copies for each node of the quiver and
 impose identification between them.
 We draw the arrows in such a way that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{i}$
\end_inset

 connects the two copies of the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th node and makes a triangle with 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{Q}_{i}$
\end_inset

, as in figure.
 Drawn in this form, it is clear that the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=2$
\end_inset

 linear quiver is a special case of the triangle quiver described in section
 ??, except that the vertical arrow is missing between the flavor nodes
 at the right end.
 The corresponding brane tiling diagram is therefore essentially the same,
 as shown in figure.
 Note that the cubic superpotentials, generated around the triangles by
 world-sheet instantons, are precisely what we need for the theory to have
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=2$
\end_inset

 supersymmetry.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As we can split the (
\begin_inset Formula $m+1$
\end_inset

)-punctured sphere into a collection of 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 trinioins, we can also break the brane tiling diagram into basic pieces.
 Each piece represents a single trinioin and is made of three zig-zag paths,
 see figure??.
 Gluing two trinions corresponds to concatenating two such diagrams side
 by side.
 In the course of this operation, we must interchange the positions of the
 zig-zag paths labeled 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 near the glued side of one of the diagrams.
 This results in an additional vertical arrow in the combined quiver, which
 is the adjoint chiral multiplet in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=2$
\end_inset

 vector multiplet used in the gauging.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us find the relationship between the convention we use for brane tilings
 and that used above.
 The R-charge 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 in the brane tiling model is given in terms of the charges of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=2$
\end_inset

 theory by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
R=R_{0}+\frac{1}{2}\sum_{i}F_{i},\quad\,R_{0}=-r+I_{3}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 The flavor charges associated to the zig-zag paths can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{a_{i}}=-F_{i},\quad\,F_{b}=-\mathcal{F}+\frac{1}{2}\sum_{i}F_{i},\quad\,F_{c}=\mathcal{F}+\frac{1}{2}\sum_{i}F_{i}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Without loss of generality, we can set
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
a_{i}=\frac{1}{\alpha_{i}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Plugging these relations into the combination 
\begin_inset Formula $(pq)^{R/2}\prod_{i}a_{i}^{F_{a_{i}}}b^{F_{b}}c^{F_{c}}$
\end_inset

 that enters the indices of the bifundamental chiral multiplets, we deduce
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
b=\frac{1}{\sqrt{t}},\quad\,c=\sqrt{\frac{t}{pq}}.\label{eq:relation_bc}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Before proceeding, we should mention a peculiarity in the 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}$
\end_inset

 case.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $N=2$
\end_inset

, the U(1) flavor symmetry of a bifundamental hypermultiplet is enhanced
 to SU(2) due to the fact that the fundamental representation of SU(2) is
 pseudoreal.
 For this reason there is no distinction between minimal and maxmal punctures,
 and each trinion can be regarded as a half-hypermultiplet in the trifundamental
 representation of 
\begin_inset Formula $SU(2)^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 This is reflected in the index of a trinion, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{I}_{B}(w,z;\sqrt{t}a)\mathcal{I}_{B}(z,w;\sqrt{t}/a)=\Gamma(\sqrt{t}\alpha^{\pm1}z^{\pm1}w^{\pm1}),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which is manifestly symmetric under permutation of 
\begin_inset Formula $a,\,z$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Surface defects in 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}$
\end_inset

 theories of class 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In [Gaiotto-Rastelli-Razamat], it was explained how to construct a surface
 defect labeled with a pair of integers (
\begin_inset Formula $r,s$
\end_inset

), and how to determine its action on the supersymmetric index.
 Although the method applies to general 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=2$
\end_inset

 theories with SU(N) flavor symmetry, here we review it in the language
 of class-
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

 theories.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose we have a class-
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

 theory 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{\mathrm{IR}}$
\end_inset

 associated to a Riemann surface that contains a maximal puncture, whose
 flavor group we call 
\begin_inset Formula $SU(N)_{z}$
\end_inset

.
 To this surface we introduce an extra minimal puncture.
 Concretely, we can do this as follows.
 First, we rename the flavor group 
\begin_inset Formula $SU(N)_{z}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $SU(N)_{w'}$
\end_inset

.
 Then, we take trinion representing a hypermultiplet (
\begin_inset Formula $Q,\tilde{Q}$
\end_inset

) with flavor symmetry 
\begin_inset Formula $SU(N)_{w''}\times SU(N)_{z}\times U(1)_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

, and glue it to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{\mathrm{IR}}$
\end_inset

 by gauging the diagonal subgroup 
\begin_inset Formula $SU(N)_{w}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $SU(N)_{w'}\times SU(N)_{w''}$
\end_inset

.
 The resulting theory 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{\mathrm{UV}}$
\end_inset

 has one more flavor symmetry, 
\begin_inset Formula $U(1)_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

, than 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{\mathrm{IR}}$
\end_inset

.
 Correspondingly, the surface associated to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{\mathrm{UV}}$
\end_inset

 has one more minimal puncture than the original surface.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The theory 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{\mathrm{UV}}$
\end_inset

 is related to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{\mathrm{IR}}$
\end_inset

 via the RG flow induced by a diagonal constant vev given to the quark 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

, or equivalently, to the baryon 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\det Q$
\end_inset

.
 The vev higgses the gauge group 
\begin_inset Formula $SU(N)_{w}$
\end_inset

 and breaks 
\begin_inset Formula $SU(N)_{w}\times SU(N)_{z}$
\end_inset

 down to the diagonal subgroup.
 Moreover, it turns the cubic superpotential 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{Q}\Phi Q$
\end_inset

 into a quadratic one that makes 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{Q}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi$
\end_inset

 massive, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi$
\end_inset

 is the adjoint chiral multiplet introduced in the gluing.
 Up to Nambu-Goldstone multiplets that survive the higgsing, in the infrared
 the multiplets we added are gone and we recover 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{\mathrm{IR}}$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $SU(N)_{w}$
\end_inset

 replaced with 
\begin_inset Formula $SU(N)_{z}$
\end_inset

.
 In effect, the minimal puncture introduced by gluing the trinion is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

closed.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 The R-charge 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{3}$
\end_inset

 is broken by the vev, but the combination 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{3}+F_{\alpha}/2$
\end_inset

 is preserved and identified with a Cartan generator of the infrared SU(2)
 R-symmetry.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To create a surface defect in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{\mathrm{IR}}$
\end_inset

, we instead give the baryon a position-dependent vev 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle B\right\rangle =\zeta_{1}^{r}\zeta_{2}^{s}$
\end_inset

.
 Here, as vefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta_{2}$
\end_inset

 are complex coordinates of the two orthogonal planes rotated by 
\begin_inset Formula $j_{p}=j_{1}+j_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j_{q}=j_{1}-j_{2}$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 Away from the origin, the effect of the position-dependent vev is the same
 as that of the constant vev, so we get 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{\mathrm{IR}}$
\end_inset

 in the infrared.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $r\neq0$
\end_inset

, however, the infrared theory is modified on the plane 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\zeta_{1}=0\}$
\end_inset

 since the vev vanishes there.
 By the same token, the theory is modified on the plane 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\zeta_{2}=0\}$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $s\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, in general we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{\mathrm{IR}}$
\end_inset

 with the insertion of a surface defect labeled with the pair of integers
 
\begin_inset Formula $(r,s)$
\end_inset

, supported on the planes 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\zeta_{1}=0\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\zeta_{2}=0\}$
\end_inset

.
 This surface defect is to be identified with the surface defect labeled
 with the pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(r\,fund,s\,fund)$
\end_inset

 of symmetric representation of SU(N) discussed in the previous section
 [Gadde-Gukov].
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The index of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{\mathrm{UV}}$
\end_inset

 has a pole in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

-plane at 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=\sqrt{t}p^{r/N}q^{s/N}$
\end_inset

, and the residue there gives the index of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{\mathrm{IR}}$
\end_inset

 in the presence of the surface defect of type 
\begin_inset Formula $(r,s)$
\end_inset

.
 The reason is the following.
 The position-dependent vev 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle B\right\rangle =\zeta_{1}^{r}\zeta_{2}^{s}$
\end_inset

 breaks 
\begin_inset Formula $U(1)_{p}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $U(1)_{q}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $SU(2)_{I}$
\end_inset

.
 At this value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

, however, the only combinations of charges that enter the trace defining
 the index are those that are preserved by the vev.
 Thus, we can still define the index in this background.
 As explained above, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{\mathrm{UV}}$
\end_inset

 flows to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{\mathrm{IR}}$
\end_inset

 plus Nambu-Goldstone multiplets in the infrared.
 The latter contains massless degrees of freedom, and they contribute to
 the index by a diverging factor, in fact a simple pole in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

-plane.
 Therefore, the residue at this pole gives the index of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{\mathrm{IR}}$
\end_inset

, together with some factor associated with the Nambu-Goldstone multiplets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We wish to compute this residue and determine the action of the surface
 defect on the index in the simplest non-trivial case, namely when 
\begin_inset Formula $N=2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(r,s)=(0,1)$
\end_inset

.
 But first, let us look at the trivial case 
\begin_inset Formula $(r,s)=(0,0)$
\end_inset

 to gain intuition of the computation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the construction of a surface defect described above, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{Q}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi$
\end_inset

 actually play no role.
 The essential point is that the vev given to the baryon built from 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 replaces 
\begin_inset Formula $SU(N)_{w}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $SU(N)_{z}$
\end_inset

 in the infrared.
 So we couple 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{\mathrm{IR}}$
\end_inset

 just to 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 for the moment.
 The index of the combined theory is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int_{\mathbb{T}}\frac{dw}{2\pi iw}\mathcal{I}_{\mathrm{V}}(w)\mathcal{I}_{\mathrm{B}}(z,w;\rho)\mathcal{I}_{\mathcal{T}_{\mathrm{IR}}}(w)=\kappa\int_{\mathbb{T}}\frac{dw}{2\pi iw}\frac{\Gamma(\rho z^{\pm1}w^{\pm1})}{\Gamma(w^{\pm2})}\mathcal{I}_{\mathcal{T}_{\mathrm{IR}}}(w),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho=\sqrt{t}/a$
\end_inset

 is the fugacity of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa=(p;p)_{\infty}(q;q)_{\infty}/2$
\end_inset

.
 In this integral, 
\begin_inset Formula $|\rho|<1$
\end_inset

 is assumed, but we can analytically continue 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 to a complex parameter and study its pole structure.
 At 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho=1$
\end_inset

, a constant vev be turned on for 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 without conflicting with the definition of the index.
 The integral should have a pole at this point in the 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-plane, and we want to calculate the residue there.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The integrand has two pairs of poles in the 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

-plane at
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
w=\rho z,\,\rho^{-1}z;\quad\quad\,w=\rho z^{-1},\,\rho^{-1}z^{-1}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 As 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\rightarrow1$
\end_inset

, the first pair of poles collide and pinch the integration contour, and
 the integral diverges.
 Likewise, the second pair also collide in this limit.
 The pole of the integral in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

-plane arises from the contributions from these poles in 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

.
 Using formula (eq:appendix), we find that the contribution from the pole
 at 
\begin_inset Formula $w=\rho z$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{1}{2}\frac{\Gamma(\rho^{2}z^{2})\Gamma(z^{-2})}{\Gamma(\rho^{2}z^{2})\Gamma(\rho^{-2}z^{-2})}\Gamma(\rho^{2})\mathcal{I}_{\mathcal{T}_{\mathrm{IR}}}(\rho z).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 The last factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma(\rho^{2})$
\end_inset

 indeed has a pole at 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho=1$
\end_inset

, with residue 
\begin_inset Formula $1/4\kappa$
\end_inset

.
 The pole at 
\begin_inset Formula $w=\rho z^{-1}$
\end_inset

 makes an equal contribution, and we get
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{Res}_{\rho=1}\left[\int_{\mathbb{T}}\frac{dw}{2\pi iw}\mathcal{I}_{\mathrm{V}}(w)\mathcal{I}_{\mathrm{B}}(z,w;\rho)\mathcal{I}_{\mathcal{T}_{\mathrm{IR}}}(w)\right]=\frac{1}{2}\frac{1}{2\kappa}\mathcal{I}_{\mathcal{T}_{\mathrm{IR}}}(z).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

As expected, the residue reproduces the index of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{\mathrm{IR}}$
\end_inset

, multiplied by some factors.
 The factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $1/2$
\end_inset

 comes from the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 has fugacity 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho^{2}$
\end_inset

, and disappears if we add the equal contribution from the pole at 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho=-1$
\end_inset

.
 The factor 
\begin_inset Formula $1/2\kappa$
\end_inset

 is the contribution from a decoupled free chiral multiplet contained in
 a Nambu-Goldstone multiplet.
 It is the inverse of the index of a free vector multiplet since higgsing
 of a U(1) gauge theory with a single chiral multiplet leads to a trivial
 theory whose index is one.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to express this result in a concise form, we introduce the notation
 of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

striking out an arrow
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in a quiver diagram to indicate that a constant vev is given to the baryonic
 operator built from the bifundamental chiral multiplet represented by that
 arrow, and the notation, what we just found is the identity
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
=4\kappa\mathrm{Res}_{\rho=1}=,\label{eq:deltaidentity}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 where the right-hand side is the delta function defined by the relation
 (??).
 This identity holds when the index of any theory with SU(2) flavor symmetry
 (or more generally, any meromorphic function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(w)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(w)=f(1/w)$
\end_inset

) is coupled to the right node.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the help of this identity, we can readily show that when a constant
 vev is turned on for 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

, the index of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{\mathrm{UV}}$
\end_inset

 reduces to that of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{\mathrm{IR}}$
\end_inset

.
 All we have to do is to look at the part of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{\mathrm{UV}}$
\end_inset

 describing the coupling to the trinion, and compute the relevant residue:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
=t=.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 In the first equality we use the identity 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:deltaidentity"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and set 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho=1$
\end_inset

, and in the second we canceled the pair of arrows making a loop.
 Thus, the vev transforms the trinion into the original flavor node of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{\mathrm{IR}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can compute the index of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{\mathrm{IR}}$
\end_inset

 in the presence of a surface defect in a similar manner.
 To indicate that the position-dependent vev 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle B\right\rangle =\zeta_{1}^{r}\zeta_{2}^{s}$
\end_inset

 is turned on, we put the label 
\begin_inset Formula $(r,s)$
\end_inset

 on the struck-out arrow:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
=4\kappa\mathrm{Res}_{\rho=p^{-r/2}q^{-s/2}}\label{eq:surfacedefect_residue}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 Then the action of the surface defect of type 
\begin_inset Formula $(r,s)$
\end_inset

 on the index is encoded in the diagram
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
(r,s).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us calculate the residue 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:deltaidentity"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $(r,s)=(0,1)$
\end_inset

.
 At 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho=q^{-1/2}$
\end_inset

, the index 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{I}_{B}(z,w;\rho)=\Gamma(\rho z^{\pm1}w^{\pm1})$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 has four sets of colliding poles in the 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

-plane.
 Two of them are 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
w=\rho qz,\,\rho^{-1}z;\quad\quad\,w=\rho z^{-1},\,\rho^{-1}q^{-1}z^{-1},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 while the other two are 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
w=\rho qz^{-1},\,\rho^{-1}z^{-1};\quad\quad\,w=\rho z,\,\rho^{-1}q^{-1}z.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 The contributions to the residue come from these poles.
 A small calculation shows that the first two sets of poles contribute in
 the same way: they set 
\begin_inset Formula $w=q^{1/2}z$
\end_inset

 and give a factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\theta(q^{-1})\theta(z^{2})$
\end_inset

 in total.
 Similarly, the contributions from the last two set 
\begin_inset Formula $w=q^{-1/2}z$
\end_inset

 and give a factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\theta(q^{-1})\theta(z^{-2})$
\end_inset

.
 Altogether, we find that the result can be expressed as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
=\frac{1}{\theta(q^{-1})}\sum_{s=\pm1}\frac{1}{\theta(z^{2s})}\Delta^{s/2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 We remind the reader that 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta(z)=\theta(z;p)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta^{\pm1/2}$
\end_inset

 act on functions of 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\Delta^{\pm1/2}f\right)(z)=f(q^{\pm1/2}z)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unlike the case of the constant vev, this identity does not cause a complete
 cancelation of the indices of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{Q}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi$
\end_inset

.
 Rather, for 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho=q^{-1/2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $w=q^{\pm1/2}z$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
=\theta\left(\frac{t}{q}z^{\mp2}\right)\theta(t).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Therefore, the effect of introducing the surface defect of type 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,1)$
\end_inset

 on the index is realized by the difference operator
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathfrak{S}_{(0,1)}=\frac{\theta(t)}{\theta(q^{-1})}\sum_{s=\pm1}\frac{1}{\theta(z^{2s})}\theta\left(\frac{t}{q}z^{-2}\right)\Delta^{s/2}.\label{eq:surfacedefectaction}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 The prefactor 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta(t)/\theta(q^{-1})$
\end_inset

 is equal to the index of a free chiral field in two dimensions, and represents
 the center-of-mass degree of freedom of the surface defect.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The difference operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{S}_{(0,1)}$
\end_inset

 acts on the fugacity for the maximal puncture on which the surface defect
 was constructed.
 This fact has a natural interpretation.
 To construct the surface defect, we first introduced an extra minimal puncture,
 and then took the residue of a pole in the fugacity of the associated flavor
 symmetry.
 The latter step can be thought of as transforming the minimal puncture
 to another kind of puncture which represents the surface defect.
 By construction, this puncture is located in the neighborhood of a maximal
 puncture contained in a trinion.
 We can take the surface defect puncture and collide it to the maximal puncture.
 The collision produces a new puncture, and defines the action of the surface
 defect on the maximal puncture.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Comparison with the transfer matrix
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us finally compare the result with the proposal.
 For clarity of presentation, take a minimal puncture in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{\mathrm{IR}}$
\end_inset

 and move it close to the maximal puncture on which the surface defect acts.
 Then the neighborhood of these punctures looks like a trinion glued to
 another maximal puncture, and is represented by zig-zag paths as in figure??.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
According to the proposal, the surface defect creates a dashed line with
 some spectral parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

, also drawn in the picture.
 It acts on the lattice model as the transfer matrix
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{Tr}\left(L^{\diamondsuit}\left(d,(c,b)\right)\right)=\sum_{s=\pm1}\frac{1}{\theta(z^{2s})}\theta\left(\sqrt{\frac{p}{q}}\frac{bc}{d^{2}}\right)\theta\left(\sqrt{\frac{p}{q}}\frac{c}{b}z^{-2s}\right)\Delta^{s/2}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 From the relation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:relation_bc"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, we see that if we set
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
d=\frac{1}{\sqrt{qt}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 the transfer matrix indeed reproduces the difference operator 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:surfacedefectaction"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, up to an overall factor which cannot be fixed by the Yang-Baxter equations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As noted in [Gaiotto-Rastelli-Razamat], the above transfer matrix is essentially
 the Hamiltonian of elliptic Ruijsenaars-Schneider model [Ruijsenaars-Schneider,
 Ruijsenaars] of type 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 This fact follows from a general result obtained in [Hasegawa].
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here we have considered only the surface defect of type 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,1)$
\end_inset

, but the general story is similar.
 The surface defect of type 
\begin_inset Formula $(r,s)$
\end_inset

 acts on the index by a difference operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{S}_{(r,s)}$
\end_inset

.
 This operator is expected to coincide with the transfer matrix for an appropria
te L-operator.
 If so, by the RLL relation, the operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{S}_{(r,s)}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $(r,s)$
\end_inset

 should commute with each other.
 This is indeed true [GRR].
 From the class-
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

 point of view, the mutual commutativity is guaranteed by the fact that
 the index is independent of the positions of punctures representing surface
 defects.
 Therefore, the order in which they act on a maximal puncture is irrelevant.
 Note that this argument also exploits the existence of an extra dimension,
 which is the M-theory circle that emerges as the type IIA brane configuration
 is lifted to M-theory.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the same reason, a surface defect puncture can be placed between any
 two punctures, whether minimal or maximal, and still yield the same result.
 From the point of view of the type IIA system, this property appears to
 be quite non-trivial and is known as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

hopping invariance
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the index [Gadde-Gukov].
 From the lattice model viewpoint, this is guaranteed by the other RLL relation
 (??).
 
\end_layout

\end_body
\end_document
